The office was quiet as I sipped my third coffee. As a Gen Xer, I sometimes feel like I‚Äôm in a social experiment. My morning began with a meeting involving our Silent Generation consultant, who still writes everything by hand. For him, using a pen became second nature decades ago. He looked at me and whispered, "I miss when people didn't have screens between them."

I tried to bridge the gap by showing him our new team Slack channel. Oftentimes, the older generation prioritizes face-to-face communication, and he is no exception. Later, I saw a Millennial manager trying to follow trends by using "Gen Z slang" in an email. It was a bit cringey, but I appreciated the effort. She places a high value on being relatable to her team. One of the Gen Zers just replied with "plz" and "LOL," which she perceived as a lack of respect, though I knew it was just their way of being brief.

At lunch, I talked to a coworker in her late 40s about life. She mentioned feeling a sense of freedom because she has nobody relying on her at home anymore since her kids moved out. Unlike the 30-somethings who are more likely to be part of the 'sandwich generation' with many dependants, she felt light. "Checking my work emails on weekends became a habit over the years," she sighed, "but now I'm trying to stop."

By the end of the day, I realized the disconnect in our office usually stems from these small habits. Whether it's the way we type or how many dependants we worry about, we are all just trying to navigate the generation gap. I packed my bag, sent a final "LOL" to the group chat, and headed home.
